As JD wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/13/2004 at 16:54:25 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>If you have a circle that is 40 foot across then how do you figure 
>the length around the outside.
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>

The circumference (distance around) a circle is calculated by
multiplying the diameter (40 feet in your case) by pi, which
is 3.14159.

So for a 40 foot diameter circle, the distance around is
40 x 3.14159 = 125.66 feet


